    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my monstera deliciosa is acting weird. the bottom leaves are turning yellow and they have some pretty dark brown spots on them. i water it about once a week and it gets decent indirect light near a window. id satisfy the drainage too, but i'm worried something is wrong. what could be causing this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your Monstera deliciosa might be suffering from a few common issues, but let's not jump to conclusions just yet. Yellowing leaves and dark brown spots could be a sign of overwatering, under-watering, or even a nutrient deficiency. If your plant is getting decent indirect light and you're ensuring proper drainage, it might be a good idea to check the soil moisture before watering again. If the soil is still moist, you might be overwatering your plant. On the other hand, if the soil is dry, you might need to water it a bit more frequently. Also, consider checking if your Monstera is getting enough nutrients. Sometimes, plants can show signs of nutrient deficiencies, such as yellowing leaves and brown spots, if they're not getting enough of the right nutrients. A balanced, slow-release fertilizer can help, but be careful not to overdo it. Remember, every plant is unique, so it might take some time to figure out what your Monstera specifically needs. Good luck!",
